lls nearly straight downward. The common$\backslash$nspecies, which morphologically appear adapted to longer dispersal,$\backslash$nachieve little lateral movement (up to 235 mm) under laboratory conditions.$\backslash$nTerminal velocity is a misleading descriptor of dispersal because$\backslash$ndiaspores with similar terminal velocities have differing movement$\backslash$npatterns. When diaspores of two species (one tall common species$\backslash$nand one short sparse species) are released in still air from their$\backslash$nnatural height, differences in maximum fall distance observed under$\backslash$nconstant height of release are lost. When dispersal is observed in$\backslash$nthe field by means of sticky seed traps, the slopes of the dispersal$\backslash$ncurves (regression coefficient of ln-transformed number of seeds$\backslash$ncaught on distance from the clump) do not differ from common and$\backslash$nsparse species, despite the fact that seeds of the common species$\backslash$nare released from greater heights. The orderly differences in dispersal$\backslash$nbehavior among species due to subtleties of morphology observed under$\backslash$nlaboratory conditions are masked in nature.},
