@article{Straub2006,
abstract = {The papilionoid legume genus Glycine Willd. consists of 24 named species (Hymowitz, 2004) with perhaps as many as nine additional species yet to be described (Pfeil unpublished data). These include G. max (L.) Merr., a model taxon and the economically important cultivated soybean. The genus Glycine is thought to be of ancient polyploid origin due to the high chromosome number of the majority of species (n = 20) compared to closely related genera (mostly n = 10 or 11, one with n = 14; Goldblatt, 1981). Additional lines of evidence exist supporting this hypothesis of polyploid origin including cytogenetic studies in haploid G. max (Crane et al., 1982), the presence of twice as many gene copies encoding leghemoglobin in Glycine as in Phaseolus vulgaris L. (n = 11; Lee and Verma, 1984), the increased ability of G. max gametophytes to tolerate the presence of extra chromosomes (Xu et al., 2000b), and the reduction in harmful effects observed in G. max monosomics (Xu et al., 2000a). Linkage mapping studies of G. max have also identified large regions of duplication, a finding consistent with an ancient polyploidy event (Shoemaker et al., 1996; Zhu et al., 1994). Glycine also includes the neopolyploids G. tomentella Hayata, G. tabacina (Labill.) Benth., G. pescadrensis Hayata, and G. hirticaulis Tindale and Craven, which all have one or more polyploid cytotypes (2n = 78 and/or 80 for each species; reviewed in Doyle et al., 2004). Although strong evidence for an ancient genome duplication in Glycine exists, the nature of that polyploidy event is still not clear (Doyle et al., 2003; Hymowitz, 2004). Kumar and Hymowitz (1989) discussed the possibility that the genus may be of allotetraploid origin, especially given evidence for other allopolyploids within the Glycininae. Singh et al. (2001) found duplicated rDNA loci in the C-genome species (G. curvata Tindale and G. cyrtoloba Tindale) relative to the number in other diploids and interpreted this as evidence that "strongly" supports a hypothesis of allotetraploid origin for the genus. Glycine species described at the time of that study exhibit diploid-like meiotic pairing (Singh et al., 2001), another observation that is expected in allopolyploids. However, diploidization during the time since an ancient autopolyploidy event could produce the same pattern of chromosome pairing. Doyle et al. (2003) found that the gene encoding chloroplast-expressed glutamine synthetase (ncpGS) was present in duplicate copy in Glycine but single copy in most other Glycininae sampled. However, the phylogeny based on this gene's DNA sequence placed the Glycine paralogues sister to one another, and thereby found no evidence to support allopolyploidy (Doyle et al., 2003). Both of these approaches have limitations. Finding duplicated rDNA loci does not test auto- versus allopolyploid hypotheses. Additionally, the presence of this duplication in one clade alone could readily be explained by lineage-specific duplication and not by polyploidy. Diploidization during the 14.5 MY (million years) or so since polyploidy (Schlueter et al., 2004) could also render the meiotic pairing observations null, because there has been much time within which multivalent formation could change to bivalent formation if the event was of an autopolyploid nature. The phylogenetic analysis of a duplicated nuclear gene (chloroplast-expressed glutamine synthetase; ncpGS) used by Doyle et al. (2003) is more promising in that this approach has some power to discriminate among the hypotheses for duplicated loci, especially in being able to exclude autopolyploidy if one Glycine gene copy is more closely related to a copy from another taxon (Fig. 1A). However, the phylogenetic approach is also limited by the inability to distinguish among autopolyploidy, independent gene duplication subsequent to divergence of Glycine from other genera, or failure to sample the genome donors that formed an allopolyploid Glycine (perhaps due to their extinction) (Fig. 1). If additional unlinked nuclear genes are used, the convergence of many of these on the same topology makes it possible to exclude independent gene duplications, but still does not distinguish between autopolyploidy and allopolyploidy where the latter has occurred with extinction or failure to sample the genome contributors. Approaches that have used multiple genes to examine polyploidy in Glycine include the analysis of synonymous substitution levels in large numbers of G. max expressed sequence tag (EST) paralogue pairs (Schlueter et al., 2004). That study showed that the Glycine genome has gone through two major rounds of duplication, one estimated at 41.6 MY ago and another at 14.5 MY ago. The more recent event is presumably shared by all species of Glycine, and thus relates to the increase in chromosome number, whereas the earlier event is shared by over 7000 species of legumes (Pfeil et al., 2005). Blanc and Wolfe (2004) in a similar study to Schlueter et al. (2004) also detected two rounds of duplication in soybean, although the estimated ages for these events are quite different due to different rate calibrations. Schlueter et al. (2004) identified the signature of two polyploid events (or large scale gene duplications) by examining the distribution of Ks values among 275 gene pairs within the G. max genome. A maximum likelihood approach fitted two normal distributions with optimum likelihood to the overall Ks distribution, indicating that two separate large-scale gene duplication events could best explain the Ks distribution, rather than one, or three or more events. Gene pairs around the mode of the younger (ca. 14.5 MY) duplication event are ideal candidates for examining the nature of this event. We focus here on addressing the question of whether Glycine was formed through an autopolyploidy or allopolyploidy event by determining the nature of the 14.5 MYA duplication event. In a novel approach to this type of problem, we selected a low-copy nuclear gene for phylogenetic analysis whose paralogues differ by a Ks value that is consistent with duplication during the 14.5 MY ago genome event found by Schlueter et al. (2004). The topological outcomes expected under each hypothesis (Fig. 1) should allow us to determine whether this gene and ncpGS agree, which would bolster support for our previous conclusion (Doyle et al., 2003) that there is no evidence for an allopolyploid origin of Glycine. ?? 2005 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.},
author = {Straub, S. C K and Pfeil, Bernard E. and Doyle, Jeff J.},
